Geoderma, 33 (1984) 191--218                                                     191  Elsevier Science Publishers B.V., Amsterdam --Printed in The Netherlands    QUANTITATIVE RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN MORPHOLOGY AND  CURRENT SOIL HYDROLOGY IN SOME ALFISOLS IN SEMIARID  TROPICAL AUSTRALIA    ROSS J. COVENTRY and JOHN WILLIAMS  Division of Soils, CSIRO, Private Mail Bag, P.O. Aitkenvale, Townsville, Queensland 4814  (Australia)  (Received August 22, 1983; revised version accepted January 23, 1984)    ABSTRACT    Coventry, R.J. and Williams, J., 1984. Quantitative relationships between morphology  and current soil hydrology in some Alfisols in semiarid tropical Australia. Geoderma,  33: 191--218.    The shallow groundwater hydrology of a sequence of red, yellow, and grey earths  (Paleustalfs, Plinthustalfs and Ochraqualfs of "Soil Taxonomy") was monitored over a  9-year period (1973--1982) along a drilled transect of 30 boreholes near Torrens Creek,  in northeastern Australia. Climatic analysis shows an aridic soil moisture regime under  which soil water surpluses should not occur, and thus significant hydromorphism would  not be expected in the soils. The present study has demonstrated, however, that profile  saturation and groundwater tables may be expected to develop at various depths in the  soils as often as 1 year in 3. Besides, strong linear relationships were found between a  number of morphological features of the soils and various hydrological regimes currently  active in the profiles: the depths to the upper limits of brown, brownish red, or red  mottles, to the upper limit of ironstone gravels, and to the maximum content of clay are  all most closely related to the mean position of the shallowest water tables observed; the  depths to grey mottles and to mottles with chromas of two or less are most directly re-  lated to the depths at which the soils are saturated for 5 weeks; the depth to the maxi-  mum content of ironstone gravels and to the base of the solum are most closely associ-  ated with the depth at which the soils are saturated for 10 to 15 weeks; and dominantly  grey colours in the strongly mottled subsola are best related to profile saturations for at  least 21 weeks. The results indicate that the gtey features present in the soil profiles could  have developed, at least in part, in response to the current soil hydrological regime.    INTRODUCTION    Experienced field pedologists invariably develop empirical relationships to  explain associations between soil profile morphological characteristics and  inferred, causative pedological processes. Over the years, these ideas have  evolved into a body of conventional pedological experience that, although  seldom underpinned by rigorous quantitative analysis, has been found to  work in the interpretation of soil features in a variety of environments. An    0016-7061/84/$03.00  1984 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V.    192    example of "pedological experience" of widespread application is the know-  ledge that, all else being equal, red soils will usually occupy better drained  sites than yellow soils (Soil Survey Staff, 1951, p. 190). Another example is  the knowledge that the occurrence of mottles with chromas of two or less in  the soil profile imply saturation at that depth for some unspecified period  throughout the year (Soil Survey Staff, 1975, pp. 48--49).  These examples highlight the qualitative nature of many aspects of our  current understanding of the hydrological significance of a variety of mor-  phological features in soil profiles. Field workers in the temperate zone in  North America (e.g., Daniels et al., 1970, 1971, 1973; Simonson and Boers-  ma, 1972; Richardson and Hole, 1979; Veneman and Bodine, 1982), and in  Europe (e.g., Van Heesen, 1970; Van Wallenburg, 1973; Moore, 1974), have  attempted to define quantitatively the soil moisture regimes that have pro-  duced certain hydromorphic soil profile features such as specific mottle  colours or patterns. The processes of mottle genesis have also been studied in  the laboratory (e.g., McKeague, 1965; Veneman et al., 1976; Vepraskas and  Bouma, 1976).  This paper seeks to quantify the depths and durations of soil profile satura-  tions that are associated with a range of morphological features in a sequence  of soils from semiarid tropical Australia. The study has been prompted by  field observations and the results of analyses of long-term rainfall records  indicating that profile saturation and groundwater tables may be expected to  develop within the solum as often as once every 3 years. An attempt will be  made to demonstrate some quantitative relationships between various soil  morphological features and the hydrological regimes currently prevailing in  the soils.    STUDY AREA AND METHODS    Regional setting    Red, yellow, and grey earths (Stace et al., 1968) are widespread soils  throughout northern Australia and mantle some 34 Mha or 37% of tropical  Queensland (Isbell and Smith, 1976). Since 1973, we have made detailed  studies of the pedology and hydrology of such soils in the Torrens Creek  area (145lYE 203'S) which lies 250--300 km southwest of Townsville  in central north Queensland (Fig. 1}. The soils are characterised by non-  calcareous profiles, massive structure, earthy fabric, mineralogy dominated  by quartz, kaolin, and iron oxides and hydroxides, low natural fertility, and  gradual texture changes through the sola of most profiles. The soils in the  vicinity of Torrens Creek have been mapped at the soil family taxonomic  level by Coventry and Fett (1982), and some of the factors controlling their  distribution patterns have been discussed previously (Coventry, 1979a,  1982). An aridic soil moisture regime prevails (Isbell and Williams, 1981)  but, because of their hard-setting surface soils and the nature of their diag-    ~]           (a) ANNUAL  RAINFALL                                                     (b)  RED, YELLOW, AND  I~      