pport  woodlands and low open woodlands dominated by Eucalyptus and/or Acacia  species.    194    The soil sequence    The sequence of 30 profiles of this study is located along an easterly-  facing midslope site, 19 km east of Torrens Creek. The soil distribution pat-  terns and topography of the landscape adjacent to the drilled transect (part  of 'Transect MTE') are shown in fig. 2 of Coventry (1982). Yellow earths,  gravelly grey earths, and loamy grey earths (some of which grade laterally  into lateritic or gleyed podzolic soils (Stace et al., 1968), all lie upslope of  much deeper red earths (Fig. 2a) that are known from nearby boreholes to  extend as red sandy clays to below 20 m (Coventry, 1982). The main char-  acteristics of each soil group on the transect are summarised in descriptions  of representative soil profiles (Table I). Lateral differences along the transect  in the depths to the morphological features analysed in this paper (mottles  of different colours, ferruginous gravels, the top of the B2 horizon, the base  of the solum, and the maximum clay content) are shown in Figs. 2b,c; mean  depths to these features in each great soil group are listed in Table II. De-  tailed descriptions are available on request of the 30 profiles studied, of  particle-size analyses for 15 of them, of the groundwater observation wells  installed along the transect, and of our water level observations (CSIRO  Aust., Div. Soils, Tech. Mem. 34/1977, 6/1979, and 10/1983). Throughout  this paper the soil colour group names of Coventry and Robinson (1981) are  used.    Climate    The climate of the study area is semiarid tropical. It is warm and dry in  winter, and hot and intermittently wet in summer. Weekly rainfall data for  a 3-year period (1945--1974) from Pentland, 50 km east of the study area,  were analysed by the method of McCown (1981) to define the onset and  cessation of the dry and "green" or wet seasons for each year. The mean    Fig. 2. Pedological and hydro