 the use of long-term montly rainfall data in this study,  the wet season is taken as December to May, and the dry season as June to  November inclusive; annual totals are calculated for the period June to May.  The rainfall distribution is both strongly seasonal and highly variable: 80%  of the mean annual total of 585 mm at Torrens Creek, and 84% of the  707 mm at Pentland falls in the wet season. This rain comes in both localised  heavy falls of short duration (we have recorded peak 1-min intensities in  thunderstorms of up to the equivalent of 480 mm/hr) and in widespread falls  of low intensity.  The 1973--1982 rainfalls include a broad range of the long-term seasonal  and annual totals recorded at Torrens Creek (Fig. 3a). Thus our observations  have not been restricted to years with atypical rainfall distributions, and our  interpretations based on these data should be valid for the long-term climatic  conditions in the area.  The only available temperature and evaporation data are from Charters  Towers, 150 km to the east, and from Hughenden, 100 km to the west (Fig.  1; Burdekin Project Committee, 1976}. Monthly average maximum tempera-  tures range from 25 to 36, and monthly average minima from 9.5 to  21. Although about 150 days per year can be expected to have tempera-  tures greater than 32, several light frosts occur in most winters. A mean  Australian Tank evaporation of 2150 mm, and a mean annual evapotranspi-  ration  of 500--600 mm are probable over the area (Commonwealth of  Australia, Bureau of Meteorology, 1970).  There is no month in the year when the mean rainfall exceeds the poten-  tial evapotranspiration estimated by the methods of Thornthwaite and  Mather (1957). A conventional.interpretation implies that a water surplus  in the soil profile would not, therefore, occur. Such an analysis, however,  does not consider the temporal distribution and seasonal variability of the  rainfall, both of which in the Torrens Creek environment contribute 