.    RESULTS    Some clear 1:1 relationships were found between the depths to soil mor-  phological features and to different soil hydrological regimes in the studied  profiles (Table III). With the exception of one soil property (the depth to  the upper boundary of the B2 horizon), the depths to all of the soil morpho-  logical features were found to be well correlated with the depth to at least  one of the soil hydrological regimes. The strongest of these relationships for  each soil morphological feature are illustrated in Fig. 6 and are discussed  below.    Soil colour characteristics and soil hydrology    The mean depths to the upper limit of brown, brownish red, or red mot-  tles increase from the yellow and grey earths to the red earths (Table II;  Fig. 2b). The correlation of the depth to the upper limit of these mottles  with the depth to the shallowest water tables observed in each of the 30 soil  profiles was found to be one of the stror~gest relationships between any of  the morphological and hydrological properties considered (Table III; Fig. 6a).  Grey mottles lie at slightly greater depths than the brown or red mottles  in the yellow and grey earths (Fig. 2b). The mean depths to grey mottles are  significantly different between soil groups and increase from the grey earths  to the yellow earths to the red earths (Table II}. The depths to the grey  mottles in the individual profiles were found to be most closely related to    207    TABLE III    Slopes and percentages of variance accounted for by simple linear regression of the form  y = bx where y is the depth to each soil morphological feature and x is the depth to dif-  ferent soil hydrological regimes  (Data are from CSIRO Aust., Div. Soils Tech. Mem., 10/1983)    Soil morphological feature    Slope   Depth to  and     the  vari-    shallowest  ance*l  water  tables    Soil hydrological regime  Depth at which the profile is  satured for:    5 weeks 10 weeks 15 weeks 21 weeks    Upper limit of brown