s no doubt that the poorly to very poorly drained grey earths  have water tables at shallower depths and for longer periods of time than the  somewhat less poorly drained yellow earths. Any water tables occurring in  the well-drained red earths are much deeper; those less than 300 cm deep  are of very short duration. A practical recognition of these differences by  landowners in the region is that the soils in which the shallow water tables  frequently develop (grey and yellow earths) have been avoided where pos-  sible in locating unsealed access roads to homesteads but are used as sites for  earth dams for surface water storage.  It is now possible to quantify such commonly observed and practically  utilized differences in the drainage status of some semiarid tropical soils.  Fig. 7 indicates that, at any particular depth, the sola of the grey earths are  saturated for about 5--8 weeks longer than are the sola of the yellow earths;  at any depth to at least 300 cm, the yellow earths are saturated for up to 21  weeks longer than are the red earths. Alternatively, Fig. 7 shows that, if  water tables are to develop in the studied soils, then they can be expected to  lie at shallower (30-60 cm) depths in the grey earths than in the yellow  earths, and about 250--450 cm shallower in the yellow earths than in the  red earths.    211    0  O,    100    200     300     400    500    Weeks of profile saturation  5     10    15    20  I     I     I     I  "*'---... @to  "-4.,%e~_\  4,%. "~  (Q  x&lt;2o  o                 o    25  I    4    I  700      I      I      I            I  Fig. 7. Durations of profile saturation at various depths in profiles comprising the three  Australian great soil groups on the transect. The values are averaged over the three periods  when water tables were observed (CSIRO Aust., Div. Soils, Tech. Mere., 10/1983 and  14/1983).    DISCUSSION    In all 30 profiles, the occurrence of mottles of any kind was consistently  restricted to that part of the solum subjected to some profile saturation. The  base of the mottle-free zone, the "matrix zone" of Moore (1974), is defined  by the upper limit to brown, brownish red or red mottles and lies above the  depths at which even the shallowest water tables have been observed. The  mean thickness of the mottle-free zone is about 40 cm thick in the moder-  ately to poorly drained yellow and grey earths and is 355 cm thick in the  well&lt;lrained red earths. A similar result was found by Simonson and Boers-  ma (1972) for a range of soils in Oregon, U.S.A., in that the depth below the  soil surface to the upper limit of mottles was also found to increase as the  drainage condition of the soil improved.  For all the profiles, the observed mottles were located in the zone of fluc-  tuating water tables that produced profile saturations of varying duration. A  similar conclusion was drawn by Van Wallenburg (1973) from a study of a    212    range of Dutch soils. The depth to the brown, brownish red, or red mottles,  the shallowest mottles in each of the 30 described soil profiles of our study,  is closely associated with the shallowest and most ephemeral of the soil  water regimes considered and is less closely related to the depths of profile  saturation for 5 weeks. If a causal relationship is inferred, this result suggests  that the development of such mottles requires some soil-profile saturation,  but that need not necessarily be of prolonged duration.  Similar hydrological conditions are associated with the distribution of  ironstone gravels in that their upper limit in the studied soil profiles is close-  ly related to the depth to the shallowest water tables observed. The maxi-  mum abundance of ironstone gravels lies at greater depths in all the soil pro-  files and was found to relate to slightly longer periods of profile saturation  (5--15 weeks).  The problem of recognizing fossil gley phenomena in soils (grey mottles,  ferruginous gravels, etc.) as relict features, related to past hydrological condi-  tions and not to those currently influencing the soil, has been recognized and  discussed by a number of authors (e.g., Ruhe et al., 1955; Schelling, 1960;  Van Heesen, 1970; Daniels et al., 1973; Van Wallenburg, 1973; Vepraskas  and Bouma, 1976). A mineralogical and micromorphological study of a  gravelly grey earth, located in the same mapping unit, but 900 m from pro-  file A of Fig. 2a, has shown that some of the abundant ironstone gravels in  the upper part of the profile are relict features (Coventry et al., 1983). These  gravels had undergone significant transportation prior to their incorporation  in the Late Tertiary sediment in which the soil subsequently developed.  Other ferruginous accumulations lying deeper in the profile and in the zone  of maximum abundance of ironstone gravels, showed clear mineralogical and  micromorphological characteristics indicative of formation in situ. Hence,  both allochthonous (relict) and autochthonous ironstone gravels are thought  to occur in the studied profiles. The time of formation of the autochthonous  features is unknown.  Relatively short durations of profile saturation (5 weeks, 10% of the year)  were found to be related to the depths to the upper limits of grey mottles  and of mottles with chromas of 2 or less. These results agree in part with the  findings of Daniels et al. (1971) from some soils in North Carolina, U.S.A.,  in which grey mottles (10 YR 6/3-7/3) were related to profile saturations for  25% of the time but not with their observation that mottles with chromas  of 2 or less were found to relate to profile saturations for as much as 50% of  the time.  For one somewhat restricted group of soils in a particular environment,  we can now make a step towards quantifying the "period of the year" for  which the Soil Survey Staff (1975) implies that mottles with chromas of 2 or  less are indicative of profile saturation. If a causal relationship is accepted,  the results of our study show that, for the range of Alfisols studied at  Torrens Creek, this "period of the year" is equivalent to 5 weeks of profile  saturation recurring once every 3 years.    213    It is clear from our analysis that grey mottles are associated with longer  periods of profile saturation than are brown or red mottles. Consequently,  the grey mottles appear at a greater depth in each soil profile than do the  redder mottles, with the exception of the poorly drained grey earth/gleyed  podzolic profiles in the vicinity of profile D in which the depths to both  kinds of mottles are coincident (Fig. 2b). Other works in the temperate zone  of the Northern Hemisphere (e.g., Daniels et al., 1971; Simonson and Boers-  ma, 1972; Van Wallenburg, 1973; Veneman et al., 1976) have also demon-  strated that red or brown mottles lie at shallower depths, and are associated  with shorter periods of profile saturation than are grey mottles.  Our results are consistent with the considerable body of field and labora-  tory evidence to suggest that grey mottles, mottles with chromas of 2 or less,  or dominantly grey colours of strongly mottled subsola are associated with  soil saturations of sufficient intensity and duration to allow reducing condi-  tions to develop in the more poorly drained soils; oxidizing conditions are  responsible for the brighter or redder colours in the better drained soils (e.g.,  Soil Survey Staff, 1951; 1975; Bloomfield, 1963; McKeague, 1965; Vepras-  kas and Bouma, 1976; Veneman and Bodine, 1982). Although profile satura-  tion is a useful parameter relating soil morphological features to soil hydrol-  ogy, Siuta (1967) and Daniels et al. (1973) have also discussed the impor-  tance of the oxygen content of the groundwater. It should be recognized  that the reducing conditions required to produce grey mottles may not al-  ways be related to high regional water tables that maintain saturation condi-  tions for long time periods (Vepraskas et al., 1974). Perched water tables  rather than high regional groundwater tables can be responsible for the phe-  nomenon (Guthrie and Hajek, 1979). Mottles can also develop in fine-  textured soil horizons immediately overlying a coarse-textured layer in pro-  files in which perched or regional groundwater tables may never occur  (Clothier et al., 1978).  The depths to the maximum content of clay in the whole soil, and to the  base of the solum in each of the 30 studied profiles are closely related to the  depths of the shallowest water tables observed and to profile saturation for  10--15 weeks, respectively. These may be fortuitous associations but we are  inclined to believe that they have some genetic significance: weathering, clay  production, and profile development must be influenced by the saturation  history of the soil profile. This idea is supported by the work of Daniels et  al. (1970, 1971) who found that as the depth to the water table increased, so  also did the solum thickness; solum thickening was thought to be impeded  by high ground water tables inhibiting the downward translocation of soil  materials. Our results show that those portions of each of the 30 studied soil  profiles lying between the maximum clay content and the base of the solum  (i.e., the major portion of each B horizon) relate to the depths of profile  saturation for less than 5 weeks to as much as 15 weeks.  The lack of correlation between the upper boundary of the B2 horizon  and any of the soil moisture conditions considered suggests that the upper    2]4    part of all the soil profiles is influenced more strongly by factors other than  fluctuating hydrological regimes in the soil. The derivation of sandy, clay-  deficient A horizons of similar soils in central north Queensland from the  erosional degradation of former termite mounds has been proposed by Holt  et al. (1980). Their conservatively estimated rates of soil accumulation indi-  cate that one generation of termite mounds could rework up to 20 t/ha of  soil, and that the 20 cm thick A horizons could have accumulated in 8000  years in a landscape where the soils may be of the order of 2 million years  old. As termite mounds are abundant in the Torrens Creek area, a similar  process may have governed the depth to the B2 horizons of the studied soils.  The soil morphological/hydrological relationships discussed in this paper  have been established for only a small number (30) and a limited range of  soil profiles (3 Australian great soil groups) at a single locality. Although  strongly site-specific, our study has quantified the hydrological significance  of a range of morphological features of soils in the semiarid tropics. These  associations between soil morphological and hydrological properties have  been established in an environment with an aridic soil moisture regime (as  defined by the Soil Survey Staff, 1975). It is an environment in which a sim-  ple water-balance analysis such as that of Thornthwaite and Mather (1957)  implies that water surpluses should not occur in any year, and where a signif-  icant development of hydromorphic soil features is most unlikely. The fact  that the opposite appears to be the case can be attributed to: the concentra-  tion of the rainfall in a marked wet season; the subdued relief of the land-  scape; the high infiltration rates and low water-holding capacities of the  soils; and the occurrence of barriers to deep drainage beneath many of the  profiles (Williams and Coventry, 1979, 1981).    CONCLUSIONS    Certain morphological features of the studied sequence of red, yellow, and  grey earths have been observed at similar depths in the soil profiles as various  hydrological regimes that occur as frequently as once every 3 years in the  semiarid tropical environment (Table IV).  Differences in soil profile saturation can be quantified at the individual  soil profile level (Fig. 5), and also at the Australian great soil group taxonom-  ic level (Fig. 7). This quantification has been carried out on two bases: dif-  ferences in numbers of weeks of profile saturation at a particular depth in  the soil or soil group, and differences in the depth in the profile to the water  that persists for a particular period.  A wide variety of soil morphological features has been related to different  soil hydrological regimes in this study in a quantitative manner that is con-  sistent with the qualitative findings of other workers elsewhere in the world.  Our results are also consistent with interpretations based on conventional  pedological experience. The close correlation of a number of soil morpho-  logical features with different shallow groundwater regimes strongly suggests    215    a close association between profile morphology and the present climate of  the area. Eight of the nine soil morphological features studied occur in the  zone of fluctuating water tables along the transect. Our results have shown  that soil profile saturations of less than 5 weeks to as much as 21 weeks, oc-  curring as frequently as once every 3 years, would appear to be sufficient for  the development of a range of hydromorphic soil characteristics. This raises  the interesting possibility of a group of old soils (Late Tertiary--Early  Quaternary in age), lying in a semiarid tropical landscape, displaying hydro-  morphic features that appear to be in harmony with their current hydrology.    TABLE IV    Summary of relationships between the depths to profile morphological features and  hydrological regimes in the studied sequence of 30 soil profiles    Morphological feature                     Hydrological regime  (i)   Upper limit of brown, brownish     Shallowest water tables observed  red or red mottles  (ii)   Upper limit of ironstone gravels  (iii)  Maximum content of clay  Upper limit of:  grey mottles  mottles with chromas of 2 or less    (i)  (ii)    Maximum content of ironstone gravels    Base of the solum    Dominantly grey colours in strongly  mottled subsola  Upper boundary of the B: horizon    Profile saturation for 5 weeks  (10% of the year)    Profile saturation for 5--15 weeks  (10--30% of the year)  Profile saturation for 10--15 weeks  (20--30% of the year)  Profile saturation for 21 weeks  (40% of the year)  Not related to any of the soil hydrological  regimes considered    Nevertheless, although causal relationships are strongly suggested by our  results, they are not proven. One of the soil morphological features studied  could not be related to any of the soil hydrological regimes analysed. Also,  the uncertainty still remains that the morphological features may be relict  and therefore owe their genesis to a previous climatic regime that may have  been similar to, or indeed quite different from that at present. Much depends  on the time of formation of the soil features and on the poorly understood  palaeoclimatic history of the region.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS    A number of the staff of CSIRO, Townsville, have assisted us in many  ways at various times throughout this long project. In particular, we are  grateful to R.S. Penny and D.E.R. Fett for expert technical assistance with    216    many tasks in the field and laboratory, and to Michele Smith for her com-  putational skills. Unpublished rainfall data and analyses were generously sup-  plied by R.L. McCown, CSIRO, Division of Tropical Crops and Pastures.  Early drafts of this manuscript have benefited from constructive criticisms  of our colleagues within CSIRO, Division of Soils: R.F. Isbell, M.E. Probert,  P.H. Walker, and D.C. van Dijk. We thank the journal referee for his percep-  tive and helpful comments.    REFERENCES    Bloomfield, C., 1963. Mobilization phenomena in soils. Rep. Rothamsted Exp. Stn.,  Engl., for 1963, pp. 226--239.  Burdekin Project Committee, 1976. Resources and potential of the Burdekin River Basin,  Queensland. Appendix 2a: Land and associated features. Aust. Gov. Publ. Serv., Can-  berra, Austr